Comment: Is this an example of that common is " " versus contains " " misconception from the set theory ? As in , neural networks contain * * decision trees the ( former are a superset of the later ) , but are not * * decision trees themselves ? My point ? Yes , one should be able to turn a neural network into a unique ( ) decision tre , by the method described in the video , but . can one turn a decision tree into a unique ( ) neural network ? Obviously , one can train a neural network on any specified decision tre , but . one can actually describe exactly the same decision tree with theoretical y ( ) infinite number of neural networks each ( of them also * * describing a number of other * * decision tres , at the same time ) . No , I definitely would not say that neural networks are * * decision tres . They do contain * * decision tres , though , and that is to be expected , following that . Neural networks are general * * function * * a proxima to rs * * and decision trees are functions , alright . I can see why one would want to equate neural networks with decision tres , though . Decision trees are easy to keep contained within specified decision ( ) boundaries , and neural networks are anything but easy to contain within ( desired decision boundaries ) . But , at best , one will only be able to predict that an AI neural ( network ) will kill everybody with some low ( , but always non zero in the case of really complex , real world AI systems ) probability , which definitely will not solve the problem of preventing with ( 10% probability ) that AI from killing everybody at some point . Unfortunately or ( fortunately , depends on one's point of view ) , I do not think that this is the right approach to AGI ( ) safety other ( than computing failures you ces / probabilities . including catastrophic ones ) , which , I am a sum ing , is what this paper is really all about , right ?

Comment: The title and abstract say nothing about the value of the paper . A N with piecewise linear activation functions is basically just chaining many functions that are linear on pieces of the domain bounded by hyperplanes . Chaining those gives us another instance of such a function , and of course you can make a decision tree that is testing these hyperplanes , determining the relevant piece and finally evaluating a select linear function at the leaf . I guess the value of the paper is making a particular efficient mapping smal ( tre ) by using the layered structure of the AN .

Comment: As usual , the critical definition of parameter " " is left vague . How many bits are required for the typical decision tree parameter " " versus the typical N parameter " " ? Decision trees are particularly amenable to this sort of analysis since a bit can be considered a decision . So in the limit , one can decompose a decision tree into an equivalent binary tree and , if there is some reason to believe one has constructed the minimum such binary tre , one has a clear understanding of the actual parameter count quantified as bits of information . This has the additional advantage of bring information theory to bear on the construction of models and , to the extent that one can construct recursive tres , discover algorithms thence the approximation of the Algorithmic Information content which , according Solomon of's 6 decade old profs , is the gold standard for regularization .

Comment: Yes this is known . It is worth pointing out that part of the claim that decision trees are interpretable comes from the fact that the training algorithm for them uses axis aligned splits . This is in contrast to the n case which typically has no such constraint in its training algorithm . In the N case looking at a single F layer , what does being in some region of space defined by what sides it lies on a bunch of non axis aligned hyperplanes mean ? Other than similarity to inputs that land in the same region , there is no simple human " " interpretation I can think of .
